<graph edgedefault="undirected"><node id="&quot;WALTER REED HEALTH CARE SYSTEM&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Walter Reed Health Care System (WRHCS) is the United States Army's comprehensive and integrated health care delivery system for the National Capital Region, providing health care to military members, their families, and federal government members."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-98a99ab8f53595716711c5a8453a35e7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;WALTER REED ARMY MEDICAL CENTER&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Walter Reed Army Medical Center (WRAMC) was the U.S. Army's flagship medical center from 1909 to 2011, located in Washington, D.C., serving over 150,000 active and retired military personnel and named after Major Walter Reed who confirmed yellow fever transmission by mosquitoes."&lt;SEP&gt;"Walter Reed Army Medical Center is a major medical facility where Major General George W. Weightman previously served as Commanding General of the North Atlantic Regional Medical Command."&lt;SEP&gt;"Walter Reed Army Medical Center is a military medical facility where issues of neglect occurred, leading to a scandal and subsequent actions by higher command."&lt;SEP&gt;"Walter Reed Army Medical Center is part of the Walter Reed Health Care System and is located in the National Capital Region, providing health care services to military members and their families."&lt;SEP&gt;"Walter Reed Army Medical Center, established after the Army Medical School in 1923, faced a major scandal involving patient neglect and unsatisfactory conditions in 2007, which led to significant public and media attention."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0b82620b32ba2d101dfd0d9365406d71&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-62be9c7a24fed6405059a1f047a1c2dc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-78047d4e38a4485cf2d496694390c264&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-98a99ab8f53595716711c5a8453a35e7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a396e27e68979245cc2726db7dbbb104</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SEVEN OTHER ARMY HOSPITALS AND HEALTH CARE CLINICS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Seven other Army hospitals and health care clinics are part of the Walter Reed Health Care System and are located in Maryland, Pennsylvania, and Virginia."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-98a99ab8f53595716711c5a8453a35e7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MARYLAND&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Maryland is a state located in the Mid-Atlantic region of the United States, known for its rich history and diverse geography."&lt;SEP&gt;"Maryland is a state where some of the Army hospitals and health care clinics of the Walter Reed Health Care System are located."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-98a99ab8f53595716711c5a8453a35e7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-44c14cd20bc9b83e77af4eed810fcdb3</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PENNSYLVANIA&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Pennsylvania is a state where some of the Army hospitals and health care clinics of the Walter Reed Health Care System are located."&lt;SEP&gt;"Pennsylvania is a state where the Vesper Boat Club is located."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-3eb64d7e941c04164d2c4510b584e35f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-98a99ab8f53595716711c5a8453a35e7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VIRGINIA&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Virginia is a state where some of the Army hospitals and health care clinics of the Walter Reed Health Care System are located."&lt;SEP&gt;"Virginia is the state where W. Dennis Kendig was born and educated."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-98a99ab8f53595716711c5a8453a35e7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b23eb5706f4e429bec0c54b18a528cf7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BUILDING 40&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Building 40 is a Georgian revival structure in the Walter Reed Army Medical Center complex in northern Washington, D.C., USA, originally housing the Army Medical School."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-98a99ab8f53595716711c5a8453a35e7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ARMY MEDICAL SCHOOL&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Army Medical School was founded by U.S. Army Brigadier General George Miller Sternberg, MD in 1893 and later became the Army Medical Center in 1923."&lt;SEP&gt;"Army Medical School, founded in 1893 by U.S. Army Brigadier General George Miller Sternberg, MD, was the world's first school of public health and preventive medicine until it became the Army Medical Center in 1923 and later the Walter Reed Army Institute of Research in 1953."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0b82620b32ba2d101dfd0d9365406d71&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-98a99ab8f53595716711c5a8453a35e7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ARMY MEDICAL CENTER&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Army Medical Center is the result of the combination of the Army Medical School and the Walter Reed General Hospital in 1923."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-98a99ab8f53595716711c5a8453a35e7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MEDICAL DEPARTMENT PROFESSIONAL SERVICE SCHOOL (MDPSS)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Medical Department Professional Service School (MDPSS) combined with the Walter Reed General Hospital in 1923 to form the Army Medical Center."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-98a99ab8f53595716711c5a8453a35e7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;WALTER REED ARMY INSTITUTE OF RESEARCH&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Walter Reed Army Institute of Research occupied Building 40 from 1953 to 1999."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-98a99ab8f53595716711c5a8453a35e7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;GEORGE MILLER STERNBERG, MD&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"George Miller Sternberg, MD is the founder of the Army Medical School in 1893."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-98a99ab8f53595716711c5a8453a35e7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;WALTER REED GENERAL HOSPITAL&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Walter Reed General Hospital combined with the Medical Department Professional Service School (MDPSS) in 1923 to form the Army Medical Center."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-98a99ab8f53595716711c5a8453a35e7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CRAIG PAVILION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Craig Pavilion is one of the four wings of Building 40, known as the first wing, built in 1924."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-98a99ab8f53595716711c5a8453a35e7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;STERNBERG PAVILION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Sternberg Pavilion is one of the four wings of Building 40, known as the second wing, built in 1932."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-98a99ab8f53595716711c5a8453a35e7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VEDDER PAVILION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Vedder Pavilion is one of the four wings of Building 40, known as the third wing, built in 1932."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-98a99ab8f53595716711c5a8453a35e7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SILER PAVILION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Siler Pavilion is one of the four wings of Building 40, known as the fourth wing, built in 1962."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-98a99ab8f53595716711c5a8453a35e7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;NORTHERN WASHINGTON, D.C.&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Building 40 is located in northern Washington, D.C., USA."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-98a99ab8f53595716711c5a8453a35e7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;14TH AND DAHLIA STREETS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"LOCATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"14th and Dahlia Streets is the specific location where the Army Medical School is situated."&lt;SEP&gt;"Building 40 is situated at 14th and Dahlia Streets."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0b82620b32ba2d101dfd0d9365406d71&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-98a99ab8f53595716711c5a8453a35e7</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;JOHNS HOPKINS SCHOOL OF PUBLIC HEALTH&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Johns Hopkins School of Public Health, founded in 1916, is another institution that claims to be the world's first school of public health and preventive medicine, competing with the Army Medical School for this distinction."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0b82620b32ba2d101dfd0d9365406d71</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;U.S. ARMY BRIGADIER GENERAL GEORGE MILLER STERNBERG, MD&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"U.S. Army Brigadier General George Miller Sternberg, MD, founded the Army Medical School in 1893."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0b82620b32ba2d101dfd0d9365406d71</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;THE WASHINGTON POST&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The Washington Post published two articles in February 2007 that exposed the Walter Reed Army Medical Center neglect scandal."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0b82620b32ba2d101dfd0d9365406d71</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;WASHINGTON, D.C.&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Washington, D.C. is the capital city of the United States and is the location of many military and medical institutions mentioned in the text."&lt;SEP&gt;"Washington, D.C. is the capital city of the United States where George Washington University Hospital is located."&lt;SEP&gt;"Washington, D.C. is the location of Howard University Hospital."&lt;SEP&gt;"Washington, D.C. is the location of Walter Reed Army Medical Center."&lt;SEP&gt;"Washington, D.C., is the location of the Walter Reed Army Medical Center where the neglect scandal took place."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0b82620b32ba2d101dfd0d9365406d71&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6a477238328e4beb6bd7d6996661beb3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e6d9d20de2b54c42af67bfe619fdd9e5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a340f0098356dc48685dc3454d675562&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a396e27e68979245cc2726db7dbbb104&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-913dd54b0f52a009be1c890bdcb998d3</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;2004&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"2004 marks the earliest reported cases of patient neglect and shoddy living conditions at the Walter Reed Army Medical Center."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0b82620b32ba2d101dfd0d9365406d71</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FEBRUARY 2007&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"February 2007 is the time when 'The Washington Post' published two articles exposing the Walter Reed Army Medical Center neglect scandal."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0b82620b32ba2d101dfd0d9365406d71</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;TRAUMATIC BRAIN INJURIES OR STRESS DISORDERS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Traumatic brain injuries or stress disorders are conditions experienced by patients at the Walter Reed Army Medical Center, which were part of the neglect scandal."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0b82620b32ba2d101dfd0d9365406d71</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;AMPUTATED LIMBS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Amputated limbs are another condition experienced by patients at the Walter Reed Army Medical Center, which were part of the neglect scandal."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0b82620b32ba2d101dfd0d9365406d71</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VERMIN-INFESTED QUARTERS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Vermin-infested quarters are a type of living condition reported at the Walter Reed Army Medical Center, which were part of the neglect scandal."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0b82620b32ba2d101dfd0d9365406d71</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;DAILY INSPECTIONS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Daily Inspections were a form of punishment imposed on soldiers for speaking to the press during the Walter Reed Army Medical Center neglect scandal."&lt;SEP&gt;"Daily inspections were used to punish soldiers for speaking to the press during the Walter Reed Army Medical Center neglect scandal."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0b82620b32ba2d101dfd0d9365406d71&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-62be9c7a24fed6405059a1f047a1c2dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VETERANS ADMINISTRATION (VA) HEALTHCARE SYSTEM&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The Veterans Administration (VA) healthcare system is mentioned as the civilian-run system where patients might be transferred if discharged from the Walter Reed Army Medical Center."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0b82620b32ba2d101dfd0d9365406d71</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VETERANS ADMINISTRATION (VA)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Veterans Administration (VA) is a civilian-run healthcare system that soldiers may be transferred to after discharge."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-62be9c7a24fed6405059a1f047a1c2dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;KEVIN C. KILEY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Kevin C. Kiley is a retired Major General and the 41st Surgeon General of the United States Army, known for his roles in various medical commands and centers, and was removed from his position due to the Walter Reed Army Medical Center neglect scandal."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-62be9c7a24fed6405059a1f047a1c2dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BUILDING 18&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"LOCATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Building 18 is a specific structure within Walter Reed Army Medical Center that experienced disrepair and mold problems."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-62be9c7a24fed6405059a1f047a1c2dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CPT MICHEAL DAKE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"CPT Micheal Dake did not implement changes to rectify the disrepair of Building 18, indicating a lack of action on his part."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-62be9c7a24fed6405059a1f047a1c2dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;COMMAND TEAM&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The Command Team refers to the leadership that took over after CPT Micheal Dake and successfully repaired and made Building 18 livable."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-62be9c7a24fed6405059a1f047a1c2dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;NEGLECT SCANDAL&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The Walter Reed Army Medical Center neglect scandal refers to a series of events that led to the relief of Major General George W. Weightman from his command at WRAMC."&lt;SEP&gt;"The neglect scandal refers to the widespread issues of neglect at Walter Reed Army Medical Center that led to public and media attention and subsequent actions by Congress and the executive branch."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e6d9d20de2b54c42af67bfe619fdd9e5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-62be9c7a24fed6405059a1f047a1c2dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MAJOR GENERAL (RET.)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ROLE"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Major General (Ret.) is a retired military rank, held by Kevin C. Kiley."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-62be9c7a24fed6405059a1f047a1c2dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FORT SAM HOUSTON, TEXAS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"LOCATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Fort Sam Houston, Texas is a military installation where Kevin C. Kiley served as the commander of the U.S. Army Medical Command."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-62be9c7a24fed6405059a1f047a1c2dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;NORTH ATLANTIC REGIONAL MEDICAL COMMAND&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"North Atlantic Regional Medical Command is a command where Eric Schoomaker served."&lt;SEP&gt;"North Atlantic Regional Medical Command is a regional command within the U.S. Army Medical Command where Major General George W. Weightman served as Commanding General before becoming U.S. Army Surgeon General."&lt;SEP&gt;"North Atlantic Regional Medical Command is a regional medical command responsible for providing healthcare services to military personnel in the North Atlantic region."&lt;SEP&gt;"North Atlantic Regional Medical Command is a regional medical command where Kevin C. Kiley served as the commander."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-78047d4e38a4485cf2d496694390c264&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e6d9d20de2b54c42af67bfe619fdd9e5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-62be9c7a24fed6405059a1f047a1c2dc&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a396e27e68979245cc2726db7dbbb104</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;U.S. ARMY MEDICAL COMMAND&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"U.S. Army Medical Command is the command responsible for the medical units of the U.S. Army, where Kevin C. Kiley served as the commander."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-62be9c7a24fed6405059a1f047a1c2dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;U.S. ARMY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"U.S. Army is the branch of the U.S. military where Kevin C. Kiley served and retired."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-62be9c7a24fed6405059a1f047a1c2dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CONGRESS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Congress is the legislative branch of the U.S. government that responded to the Walter Reed Army Medical Center neglect scandal with actions such as resignations of several high-ranking officers."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-62be9c7a24fed6405059a1f047a1c2dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;EXECUTIVE BRANCH&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The Executive Branch, including the President and other executive officials, responded to the Walter Reed Army Medical Center neglect scandal with actions such as resignations of several high-ranking officers."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-62be9c7a24fed6405059a1f047a1c2dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ERIC SCHOOMAKER&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Eric B. Schoomaker is a former U.S. Army Lieutenant General who served as the 42nd Surgeon General of the U.S. Army, Commanding General of the U.S. Army Medical Command, and previously as Commanding General of Walter Reed Army Medical Center."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-a396e27e68979245cc2726db7dbbb104</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MAJOR WALTER REED&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Major Walter Reed (1851-1902) was an army physician who confirmed that yellow fever is transmitted by mosquitoes rather than direct contact, leading to the naming of Walter Reed Army Medical Center."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-a396e27e68979245cc2726db7dbbb104</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FOREST GLEN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Forest Glen is the location of Walter Reed Army Medical Center."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-a396e27e68979245cc2726db7dbbb104</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;GENERAL OFFICER MANAGEMENT OFFICE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"General Officer Management Office is a temporary billet where Eric Schoomaker was assigned pending retirement."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-a396e27e68979245cc2726db7dbbb104</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PENTAGON&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Pentagon is the location where Eric Schoomaker was assigned pending retirement."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-a396e27e68979245cc2726db7dbbb104</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MAJOR GENERAL&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ROLE"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Major General is the grade in which Eric Schoomaker retired."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-a396e27e68979245cc2726db7dbbb104</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PENDING RETIREMENT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ROLE"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Pending Retirement is the status indicating Eric Schoomaker’s assignment before his official retirement."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-a396e27e68979245cc2726db7dbbb104</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FOREST GLEN ANNEX&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Forest Glen Annex is a 136-acre U.S. Army installation located in the Forest Glen neighborhood of Silver Spring, Maryland, USA. It has housed various military and research institutions since 1999, including the Walter Reed Army Institute of Research (WRAIR) and the Naval Medical Research Center (NMRC)."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-78047d4e38a4485cf2d496694390c264</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;U.S. ARMY SURGEON GENERAL&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"U.S. Army Surgeon General is a high-ranking position within the U.S. Army Medical Corps, held by Major General George W. Weightman starting from December 11, 2007."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-78047d4e38a4485cf2d496694390c264</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SILVER SPRING, MARYLAND, USA&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Silver Spring, Maryland, USA is a city in Maryland, USA, where the Forest Glen Annex is located. It is known for its diverse neighborhoods and proximity to the Capital Beltway."|</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-78047d4e38a4485cf2d496694390c264</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BROOKVILLE ROAD&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"LOCATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Brookville Road is a road that runs near the Forest Glen Annex, helping to define the boundaries of the installation."|</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-78047d4e38a4485cf2d496694390c264</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ARMY AND AIR FORCE EXCHANGE SERVICE (AAFES)&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The Army and Air Force Exchange Service (AAFES) is a U.S. Department of Defense organization that provides goods and services to military personnel and their families."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e6d9d20de2b54c42af67bfe619fdd9e5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;WALTER REED NATIONAL MILITARY MEDICAL CENTER&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Walter Reed National Military Medical Center is a medical center that provides healthcare services to military personnel and their families."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e6d9d20de2b54c42af67bfe619fdd9e5</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;GEORGE W. WEIGHTMAN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Major General George W. Weightman was a U.S. Army Family Medicine physician and served as the commander of the North Atlantic Regional Medical Command and Walter Reed Army Medical Center (WRAMC) until March 1, 2007."</data>
